title: For Sale:  Sightmark 7x Tactical Magnifier with Slide-to-Side QD mount
postcontent:
Gently used, in excellent condition. Flips to the side for quick switching between your holographic/red dot weapon site and magnification. Mount is also a Quick Detach.

From the manufacturer:
Featuring a wider edge-to-edge resolution and tighter tolerances for high caliber weapons, the Sightmark® series of Tactical S.T.S. Magnifiers are multi-functional weapons accessories featuring a slide-to-side mount. Offering the ability to quickly move the magnifier out of the way without having to detach the unit, the 7x Tactical Magnifier S.T.S. gives shooters quick target acquisition capabilities. The device is designed for use in conjunction with holographic, collimated reflex, and other compatible weapons sights, giving the shooter the benefit of a reflex sight and scope in one combination.

The 7x Tactical Magnifier S.T.S. increases the magnification of the accompanying sight for greater sighting range and improves target recognition significantly at long-range distances. Engineered to assist in quick target acquisition up to 350 yards and accurate target shooting at 200 yards, the 7x Tactical Magnifier S.T.S. also features extended eye relief for comfort, a wide field-of-view and high quality multi-coated optics for improved visibility and clarity. Designed to work with EOTech, Aimpoint, Trijicon and other brands, the 7x Tactical Magnifier S.T.S. can be securely mounted on most picatinny and weaver mounts. Its lightweight, weather proof and shatter-proof housing provides durability in all elements.

title: For Trade:  Dragunov Sniper Rifle - NDM-86 .308 Nato
postcontent:
If you know what this is then you know what they are worth. I am looking to trade it for a Firebird - Trans AM or Formula. Project car must be running and not wrecked. I may be able to add some addtional cash for the right deal. 

NOTE: I am not interested in any other trades, so do not waste our time. I will not reply to you. I am NOT hard up for money. Estimated value is $4K - $5K.

Chinese Dragunov in 7.62x51, the only exact copy of the original Russian design. Rifle is wearing the current issue military polymer stockset. This makes the rifle more accurate as wood can expand or contract depending on the weather, changing the accuracy of the rifle. The polymer set does not do this, and is what's currently in use with the military. These rifles have been banned from import into the United States since the early 1990's and will likely remain so. The website SniperCentral lists the officially adopted sniper rifles of 61 countries, and the Dragunov represents 23 of them. The next most popular rifle (SSG-69) has only been adopted by 5 nations. Coming into service in 1963 the Russian rifle has become famous. This rugged and absolutely reliable system boasts a heavy-duty milled receiver that won't stop. The reliability of the system, combined with the semi-automatic rate of fire which allows quick follow-up shots if you miss your target the first time, and the hard-hitting 7.62 caliber round all make the Dragunov the ideal sniper rifle. A communist sniper issued a Dragunov rifle in the Afghan war stated that he felt confident hitting people out to 800 yds with one shot, and vehicles up to 1000 yds. The Chinese are the only ones who made a direct clone of the Russian Dragunovs and were helped by the Russians during production. Some Chinese rifles have even been found to be re-stamped Russian rifles. The 7.62x51 version is the most accurate of them all and was only made by the Chinese. It combines the durability of the Russian Dragunov with the accuracy of the American 7.62x51(.308) bullet. These rifles can outshoot the stock M14/M1A and AR10 rifles, and the only reason they are not in any U.S. arsenals currently is because it wasn't designed by an American. With the .308 chambering and the military furniture, this is the absolute most accurate Dragunov rifle you can buy. With no more coming into the country, these are undoubtedly good investments that you can take out and enjoy. This one is in excellent condition.   I will pull add if I don't get any viable offers or if I trade it.

title: For Sale:  Savage 110 Left Hand .22-250 Varmint 1968 Matte Blued w/ Bishop Stock
postcontent:
I picked this up earlier this year. I told myself I was never going to sell it, since someone put a lot of time, love, and skill into building it, but I've decided that I'll be better suited with a .223 for what I'm using the gun for, so I'm going to use this to finance another (I'm sure I'll regret selling it, but a different gun I'll actually use beats one sitting in the corner that I don't).

Savage 110 Left Hand .22-250 Remington Varmint (Intermediate 4.522" action). 1968 build by proofmark/date code on the barrel. 22" light varmint contour barrel, measures .585" @ muzzle, and is basically a straight taper from chamber to muzzle (as far as my eye can tell).

The receiver/barrel/trigger guard/floorplate all wear a matte blued finish, the bolt has been polished throughout.

Period CE Bishop walnut stock with rollover cheekpiece, which has been pillar and glass bedded. I just put a brand new Pachmayr basketweave pad on it to replace the original one which was pretty firm.

Trigger is original three-screw. I've replaced the spring with one .039 dia, trigger breaks @ 1.75lb, and is crisp. I will include the original wire if you like.

I will include a Score-High singleshot follower that I modified to work with this action (their followers aren't really meant for intermediate actions, but I added a spacer to the back and reprofiled it, and it works flawlessly).

Scope (Weaver V-16 Classic), and rings (Burris Signature) are NOT included at this price, but can be made available for additional $

I will include the attached set of Redfield scope bases.

Burned up a 40 count box of Winchester white box playing around with it and sighting it in, best group was just under 1" (3 shot) @ 100 yard, before I made the trigger better. Word of advise, stay away from the Winchester 40 ct 22-250, they are very inconsistent. Never got around to load development (I do have a recipe given to me from the previous owner you can use as a starting point), but I'm sure just about any shell would be better than what I used.

$550 (plus actual shipping from 14623 if you aren't local).

Happy to take additional pics @ your request.

Please note, I intend to use the funds from this to finance another gun I have my eye on. If the other one sells, or I decide to keep this one, I may pull the ad @ any time, so if you are interested, contact me ASAP.

title: For Sale:  Ready to Fly Quadcopter w/1080P HD Camera Extras
postcontent:
If you'd like to own a very stable, powerful, portable drone/multirotor/quadcopter for aerial photography or just to fly around for fun... this is the all inclusive deal for you! Everything is already set up and ready to go - no programming required. All components are in absolutely excellent condition. This package includes all of the following: 

RC Eye One Xtreme w/ installed Spektrum Rx
Spektrum DX6i w/batteries
Mobius HD Action Cam (http://youtu.be/oqQ77nXSfVw)
OneStation Battery Charger - charges 4 batteries at once!!!
USB Battery Charger - w/ this and other charger all 5 batteries can be charged at same time!
5 Batteries (4 are high capacity, 1 standard)
2 Carrying Cases as pictured for easy transport
Aerial Kit - Camera Mount / Longer Legs (short legs also included)
2 Extra Brushless Motors
10 Complete Sets of Props
2 Extra Canopies (Red and Black)
Extra Frame

I've got over $650 invested in this package not to mention the set up time. If you have any questions about this just let me know. After seeing some other listings out there I thought I might post a few things you might want to think about and price out if you're buying your first multirotor:

How do I charge the batteries? Do I need to buy a special lipo charger? Can I charge all my batteries at once? How much are extra batteries? (you'll always want more than one) How much is it going to cost to repair if I crash? Do I need to buy a transmitter and receiver before I can fly? Will I need to program the flight controller or transmitter? How am I going to transport easily without damaging anything?

In this package it includes EVERYTHING you need and can fly right away. Yes, you can buy other things that fly cheaper than this, but there will be many more expenses down the road and you'll end up spending a lot more.
